<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-05-15T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-05-15T00:00:00-05:00" n="1106" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1106">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.11/4303.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Brazilian Minister at Mexico
                                    City</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Brazilian Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico City</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-05-15">
                                    <hi rend="italic">May 15, 1914</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>25. I have information from British Minister here that at the suggestion
                            of American Consul at Ensenada, Lower California, some sixty or
                            seventy-five Americans have concentrated at San Quentin and that they
                            are suffering all kinds of hardships due to their lack of means and the
                            difficulty of reaching them to furnish assistance. It seems therefore
                            imperative that a transport be sent there immediately. <pb facs="0804" n="688" xml:id="pg_688"/> I have asked the British Minister to
                            instruct his nearest Consul to furnish assistance at our expense, but
                            while he promised to telegraph he fears his Consul may not have the
                            funds to do so, or that available communication may not be at hand.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cardoso de Oliviera</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>